---
import Doc from '../../layouts/Doc.astro';
import Callout from '../../components/Callout.astro';
import FoundationPager from '../../components/FoundationPager.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/url';

const title = 'Cognitive debt';
const description =
  'Technical debt is code you wish was cleaner. Cognitive debt is code you wish you understood. AI accelerates the second while paying down the first. That is the real risk.';
---

<Doc title={title} description={description} section="foundation">
  <p class="doc-lede">
    Technical debt is code you wish was cleaner. Cognitive debt is code you
    wish you <em>understood</em>. AI accelerates both. But it pays down
    technical debt and accelerates cognitive debt at the same time. That is
    the real risk.
  </p>

  <h2>The mechanism</h2>
  <p>When an agent produces code faster than the team can internalise it, two things happen:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Cognitive surrender.</strong> Developers accept the diff because
      it passes tests, without forming a mental model of why it works. Fine
      for one PR. Fatal across a quarter.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>Knowledge erosion.</strong> The team's collective theory of the
      system drifts away from the system itself. When something breaks in
      production, no one knows where to look.
    </li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    Cognitive debt is invisible to linters and tests. It only surfaces during
    incidents.
  </p>

  <h2>Three kinds of debt</h2>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Type</th><th>Indicator</th><th>AI's effect</th><th>Repayment</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Technical</strong></td>
        <td>Duplication, poor structure, dead code</td>
        <td>Reduces it (AI refactors well)</td>
        <td>Automated linting, refactor passes</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Cognitive</strong></td>
        <td>Slow onboarding, loss of confidence, "no one understands X anymore"</td>
        <td>Accelerates it (generates faster than humans read)</td>
        <td>Active design participation, plan reviews</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Intent</strong></td>
        <td>"Why was this built this way?" has no answer</td>
        <td>Accelerates it (the agent makes choices from training patterns, not from your context)</td>
        <td>ADRs, negative-space docs, rationale in PRs</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>
    Intent debt is the most subtle. It looks like nothing went wrong. The code
    works. But the next time someone needs to change it, they have to
    reverse-engineer the choices from scratch.
  </p>

  <h2 id="context-rot">Context Rot: four failure modes in long sessions</h2>

  <p>
    Even with good context files in place, long-running agent sessions
    degrade. The conversation history accumulates, the agent runtime compacts
    it, and the original rules get summarised into vague generalisations. The
    same agent that wrote pristine type-safe code in hour one starts writing
    unannotated functions in hour four.
  </p>

  <p>The 2026 playbook taxonomy names four distinct rot patterns. Each has a different mitigation.</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Rot</th><th>What it looks like</th><th>Mitigation</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Poisoning</strong></td>
        <td>The agent uses deprecated APIs, outdated parameters, or stale syntax. The model's training data contradicts the current code.</td>
        <td>Version-controlled deprecation logs; explicit "do not use X, use Y" rules; the <a href={url('commands/audit/')}><code>audit</code></a> command's stale-context check.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Distraction</strong></td>
        <td>Irrelevant rules fire while the agent is editing in an unrelated area. SQL conventions distract while editing a React component.</td>
        <td>Scoped rules via <a href={url('commands/scope/')}><code>scope</code></a>; strict token budgets in always-apply rules; the split-file architecture.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Confusion</strong></td>
        <td>The agent conflates two similar-but-distinct objects. <code>User</code> and <code>UserAccount</code>, <code>Order</code> and <code>Invoice</code>.</td>
        <td>Precise namespace mapping in conventions; before/after code examples; ADRs that name the distinction.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Clash</strong></td>
        <td>Two rules in active memory contradict. Output paralysis, or whichever rule the agent saw last "wins" silently.</td>
        <td>Cross-file consistency check in <code>audit</code>; one canonical source (<code>.context/conventions.md</code>); centralised governance.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p>
    The most common rot at hour two of a session is Distraction; at hour four
    it's Poisoning (the original rules have been summarised away). The
    <a href={url('commands/verify/')}><code>verify</code></a> hook plus the
    <a href={url('commands/audit/')}><code>audit</code></a> command catch
    most cases. Frequent session clears (<code>/clear</code> in Claude Code,
    equivalent elsewhere) force the agent to reload fresh configurations from
    disk rather than relying on compacted history.
  </p>

  <h2>The four repayment practices</h2>

  <p>The moves high-performing teams have converged on. Every command in this skill is built to support at least one.</p>

  <h3>1. Atomic interaction and review</h3>
  <p>
    Large features get broken into small, atomic changes. Each change is
    reviewed individually. The human stays the architect of the logic; the
    agent is the implementer.
  </p>
  <p>
    Commanded by: <a href={url('commands/plan/')}><code>plan</code></a> (names
    the smallest reasonable unit),
    <a href={url('commands/verify/')}><code>verify</code></a> (ensures each
    unit has its own check).
  </p>

  <h3>2. Externalise intent</h3>
  <p>
    Capture the <em>why</em> in files the agent will read on future runs. Two
    flavors: <strong>ADRs</strong> ("we chose X over Y because Z") and
    <strong>negative-space docs</strong> ("we considered W and rejected it
    because V"). Without the negative space, the agent will eventually suggest
    W again, because W is in its training data and your "we do not do W here"
    never made it into the repo.
  </p>
  <p>Commanded by: <a href={url('commands/adr/')}><code>adr</code></a>, <a href={url('commands/init/')}><code>init</code></a>.</p>

  <h3>3. Plan Mode discipline</h3>
  <p>
    Before any non-trivial implementation, the agent produces a plan: files,
    approach, verification, rollback. The human reviews it as a contract before
    any code is written.
  </p>
  <p>Commanded by: <a href={url('commands/plan/')}><code>plan</code></a>.</p>

  <h3>4. Verification-first workflows</h3>
  <p>
    The most reliable way to manage AI output is to give the agent rock-solid
    verification. Tests, linters, typecheckers, build commands. The agent
    iterates until verification passes; you only review the final state.
  </p>
  <p>Commanded by: <a href={url('commands/verify/')}><code>verify</code></a>.</p>

  <h2>What success looks like</h2>

  <p>A team has repaid cognitive debt when:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>A new engineer joins, reads the context files, and is productive in hours not weeks.</li>
    <li>An incident happens and the on-call can pinpoint the relevant ADR within five minutes.</li>
    <li>The agent's first-pass output matches the team's conventions without correction more than 80% of the time.</li>
    <li>Refactors do not require a synchronous meeting to explain the original intent.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    If any of those is not true, there is debt to repay. Run
    <a href={url('commands/audit/')}><code>audit</code></a> to find which kind.
  </p>

  <Callout label="Source" tone="mute">
    <p>
      <a href={url('blueprint/#cognitive-debt')}>2026 Context Engineering
      Blueprint: Eliminating Cognitive Debt</a>. The concept has gained
      board-level urgency in 2026. The danger is invisibility.
    </p>
  </Callout>

  <FoundationPager slug="cognitive-debt" />
</Doc>
